Foundation.Core.Comment.Foundation.Core.ModelElement.name: "source" describes the pre-conditions or input-state; "product" the post-conditions or result-state.
An "eventLocation" property is inherited from Event. This should be the location of the *Observation Event* - i.e. the location of the sensor or instrument at the moment of observation.

Observations are soft-typed concerning their semantics. This is necessary since the set of possible PhenomenonDefinitions is essentially infinite, especially given the fact that a PhenomenonDefinition may be compound.

eventTime The eventTime is modelled as a generalized TimeObject. It will often be a geometric primitive, such as an instant or period, but (e.g.) recurrent events may be associated with a temporal geometric complex. (This is the primary reason that Event is not based on gml:DynamicFeature, for which the "validTime" property is a Time Primitive)
When the Procedure is a Sensor, this dependency is a directed association with the rolename "observable".

Some classes substitutable for AbstractFeature (e.g. xmml:Site, xmml:Specimen) know about "relatedObservations" on the source end of the association. However, in general the association is unidirectional.

The Observation feature supports an event-centric view. The "observation" description is a map of all of the properties associated with a particular information capture event, including its result. This contrasts with the Sensor feature, which provides a process-centric viewpoint. The "sensor system" description is effectively a map of of the properties of all potential information capture events _except_ the results.

The procedure that is the target of this association will often be a description of a generic procedure, instrument, etc. However, if it is necessary to record instance-specific details, parameters, inputs, etc, then a specific procedure-instance should be used. For example, a CategoryObservation event will use a classification-procedure that may depend on more primitive observations - e.g. a set of prior measurements. As part of the description of the procedure it may be useful to be able to record these sources or inputs. While these are observation-instance information, I think it is preferable to partition these considerations with the "Procedure" rather than promoting special properties ("inputs", "source") up to the Observation class. This is consistent with some mission-specific parameters being associated with the sensor, as is done in SensorML. However, the most appropriate partioning of the generic (static) and instance specific (dynamic) information between the Observation feature and the Procedure/Sensor is to some extent arbitrary. This is very relevant to the issue of choosing between Registry and Sensor-Service interfaces for key information.

The procedure (sensor model) defines how elements of the result map onto elements of the target. This includes (1) mapping components of a complex result to thematic components of the phenomenon (2) mapping elements of a composite result to spatio-temporal components of the target (e.g. pixels)
Target Location may be provided by * the Sensor Model (remote sensors) * the sensor location (in situ sensors) * the sampling location (specimens)
The Procedure must be commensurate with the Phenomenon being observed. The phenomenon-definition is treated as a first-class property of observation in order to support discovery and data fusion.
This type may be used as the type of the Observation/result where the value is provided as an independent resource identified by a URI.

Generic concrete observation type, in which the result is "anyType". Note that this class is a *sibling*, rather than parent, to the specialized convenience observation types. Note that he result may be a pointer to a value (stream) available out-of-band (e.g. from another service). This supports the case where the client is primarily interested in listening to a result-stream, or where the result is expressed in some other conventional format (e.g. imagery). In this contect the Observation instance provides the "metadata" for the result, primarily concerning the data-capture event.
Concrete observation type in which the result is an interleaved stream. The structure and encoding of the stream are provided in the adjacent properties.

Site is the top of a hierarchy of classes describing features whose primary role is to provide locations for sampling and in-situ observations, such as Station, Traverse, Section, Borehole, Flightline. Instances of these feature-types are not defined by the variation of any intrinsic property, such as a geological concept, but are artefacts of the observation process, either conceptual or constructed.
